33:48.912 --> 34:18.683
going here damn it stay up let's get up go get going

33:48.912 --> 34:18.683
um Well, did I push them too hard or did the division 
commander push me too hard? That doesn't ever

34:28.841 --> 34:30.984
enter anybody's mind. That never really enters 
anybody's mind. I don't think you can be pushed too

34:38.694 --> 34:42.078
hard. There's an inspiring thing about battle to 
succeed and you always look to the leader because

34:42.098 --> 34:50.509
he's the oldest

34:53.290 --> 35:21.711
you would you hope with the most judgment and most 
wisdom and uh you know when you're 25 years old and

34:53.290 --> 35:21.711
you command 3,000 people I guess I was the oldest

34:53.290 --> 35:21.711
uh as little judgment and wisdom as I had I guess I 
was the oldest everybody looked I know my sergeant

34:53.290 --> 35:21.711
major was 19 with one year out of University of 
Tennessee and his name is Rip Thornton. He's CPA

35:27.269 --> 35:28.470
now. And he is absolutely phenomenal because my 
sergeant major got killed on the beach in Normandy

35:29.312 --> 35:40.387
who had about 15 years service. What a heck of a guy. 
I had no one. You don't get replacements for those

35:46.235 --> 35:48.399
people. So I just took my clerk who had what we 
called T-4 back in those days. He'd be a buck

35:59.982 --> 36:04.407
sergeant now, 19 years old. You're the sergeant 
major. If you haven't learned from him, the dead

36:08.232 --> 36:16.422
one, I said, you and I will make a few mistakes 
together. He said, Roger that, sir. So we went on

36:20.628 --> 36:21.769
with it. Now let's go back to North Africa. Tell me 
about your campaign now. North Africa was a

36:29.118 --> 36:39.253
disaster. The whole campaign in North Africa 
started out as kind of after the landing. After the

36:46.775 --> 36:59.651
Second Armored Division and the Ninth Infantry 
Division landed down at Puerto Leote and Safi and

36:46.775 --> 36:59.651
took Casablanca, they went to Cork Forest and 
retrained there. We fought the French for three

36:59.691 --> 37:01.574
days. The French finally gave up. And then— 
Actually, you were in combat with the French? With

37:09.844 --> 37:10.405
the French, yeah. You fought the hell out of them, 
yeah. Really? Oh, yeah. Three days. Mm-hmm. So

37:15.277 --> 37:20.783
they get capitulated on the 11th of November. You 
got to understand, I was not there. I was down in

37:25.028 --> 37:29.373
another census or something. But I got there 
immediately after that and went back to my

37:30.314 --> 37:39.124
regiment in 67.

37:41.872 --> 37:43.034
was the 68th. When it started out, we reorganized 
and we ended up with two regiments. We just had a

37:47.139 --> 37:57.252
66th and a 67th regiment because the 68th was a 
light tank regiment and we split it up amongst the

37:47.139 --> 37:57.252
other two medium regiments. Because we just had so 
damn many tanks, you couldn't handle them all in

37:57.273 --> 38:00.777
the division. So how many were you in charge of? I 
was in charge of, at the end of the war. No, right at

38:08.167 --> 38:09.208
the beginning. Oh, 17. Okay. Seventeen. Three 
platoons of five inch in each and two in the

38:12.565 --> 38:16.609
headquarters. Okay. And you usually rode in the 
first one? Rode in the first tank. Yeah, company

38:22.355 --> 38:23.356
commander tank. Okay. And then you uh—after

38:23.997 --> 38:33.146
the— Where was the first action that you saw? Up in 
Tunisia.

38:38.211 --> 38:40.313
The background on that is— The 1st

38:42.520 --> 38:52.271
Armored Division and the 1st Infantry Division 
had landed at Oran, Algiers. Simultaneously with

38:53.612 --> 39:07.027
the 2nd Armored and the 9th Infantry landing down 
at Casablanca and taking Casablanca.

39:07.047 --> 39:11.532
The High Command was worried about

39:13.132 --> 39:23.046
We were in French Morocco and we had the other 
Morocco there, Spanish Morocco. We didn't know

39:24.848 --> 39:29.955
which way the Spanish were going to go and they'd 
been playing footsie with the Germans. A lot of

39:30.035 --> 39:34.802
Germans down there in Spanish Morocco and we 
thought that they were going to try pull some kind

39:35.120 --> 39:48.633
of leg up and sabotage the deal to bust our supply 
lines against Rommel's forces over there in the

39:35.120 --> 39:48.633
8th Army, British 8th

39:35.120 --> 39:48.633
Army. Meantime, the 1st Infantry and the 1st 
Armored go through Algiers into Tunisia, and

39:48.653 --> 39:58.183
they're up at Kasserine Pass in the general area. 
Had a corps commander named General Friedenthal

40:04.853 --> 40:20.316
His performance along with the 1st Armored 
Division commander's performance was not

40:04.853 --> 40:20.316
to the high command's liking and wasn't 
acceptable to anybody, so they both were

40:04.853 --> 40:20.316
relieved. Meantime, Georgie, they had a hell of a 
lot of losses, tank losses.

40:32.731 --> 40:43.524
Georgie still commanded the Western Task Force,

40:32.731 --> 40:43.524
which was the second arm of the 9th Army Division. 
General Ernie Harmon had the

40:43.544 --> 40:50.833
second Army Division at the time. Georgie was 
selected to go take that second corps under

40:50.853 --> 40:56.680
Kasserine Pies. And doing so, he took tank units 
and officers with him, kind of borrowed them out of

40:57.892 --> 41:14.877
the 2nd Armored Division to go up there to 
reestablish until they could get replacements,

40:57.892 --> 41:14.877
get tanks, and that sort of stuff, because he had to 
get on it. And that's how I got involved up there.

41:18.222 --> 41:22.348
And so you were one of the ones that he took. And then 
I ended up at Berzerdi. at the end of the war. The

41:27.999 --> 41:33.645
rest of the Second Armored Division was preparing 
for Sicilian operation. But that's where you met

41:33.665 --> 41:37.108
Rommel, up at the Kasserine Pass? No, I fought some 
of his units. I had met him. Yeah, that's where I

41:41.252 --> 41:43.334
went. You fought some of his units? Yeah. Now would 
you comment on the quality of Rommel's tank

41:46.978 --> 41:54.325
commanders?

41:54.727 --> 41:58.131
I guess they're the best soldiers that I've ever 
fought against. They're not as tenacious

42:00.354 --> 42:04.879
as the Communists. I don't know what the 
Communists do to their soldiers, but the tenacity

42:07.001 --> 42:16.392
of them is pretty damn effective, pretty strong. A 
German soldier, he had a warrior. like American.

42:26.059 --> 42:36.450
When he's totally surrounded, he doesn't fight 
the last man and that sort of crap.

42:36.470 --> 42:40.275
I haven't seen many American units do that either. 
There's no hatred, I don't believe, among

42:42.357 --> 42:46.322
soldiers. In other words, your men didn't hate the 
Germans that much? They sort of respected them as

42:51.788 --> 42:53.590
soldiers? Yeah, you've got to respect them or 
they're going to kick hell out of you. You know what

42:57.471 --> 42:58.593
I'm talking about? You've got to respect their 
capabilities. And by God, they better respect

43:02.537 --> 43:07.163
yours, too, or he'll get his damn clock cleaned. So 
that's the way it is amongst warriors, you know. No

43:10.967 --> 43:13.270
question about it. Hell, you know, you don't hate 
the enemy as a person. Much dislike as I have for

43:22.072 --> 43:32.504
communism,

43:22.072 --> 43:32.504
those soldiers out there are people, you know. And 
he's out there under orders to kill you or to do

43:33.885 --> 43:38.330
this, that, and the other. And hopefully someday 
our country will get back to the fact that it won't

43:38.530 --> 43:49.142
be a sin to kill an enemy soldier when you're in 
battle instead of trying to love him to death. That

43:51.265 --> 44:03.823
happens in any country wherein politicians get 
involved in telling generals how in the hell to

43:51.265 --> 44:03.823
fight the battle and what targets he ought to hit 
and that sort of stuff. When you get into that, you

44:03.843 --> 44:13.176
can be criticized for saying to the press that 
you're going to kill the enemy before he gets back

44:03.843 --> 44:13.176
in Cambodia. And you can get criticized to beat 
hell like I did. Well, I was out to destroy the

44:19.919 --> 44:24.704
enemy, and I had to keep them from killing my 
soldiers. Yeah, well, we're going to get to that.

